%[text] # MATH2089 Lab 3
%[text] In this week's lab, we will go about computing probabilities of various distributions. 
%[text] ## Question 1
%[text] Let $X\\sim\\text{Ber}(p)}$, so that $\\mathbb{P}\\{X = 1\\} = p = 1 -  \\mathbb{P}\\{X = 0\\}$. We can think of $X$ has measuring the outcome of a coin toss, where *Heads*$\\equiv$1 and *Tails*$\\equiv$0 and the probability of tossing Heads is $p$. Let $X\_{1},\\dots,X\_{n}$ be an independent sequence of $\\text{Ber}(p)$ random variables and let $Y = \\sum^{n}\_{i = 1}X\_{i}$. Then $Y\\sim\\text{Bin}(n,p)$. Here, we analogously think of $Y$as the number of Heads we observe from a sequence of $n$ coin tosses where the probability of heads is again $p$. Clearly $Y\\in\\{0,\\dots,n\\}$ and has corresponding density $f(y) = \\binom{n}{y}p^{y}(1 - p)^{n - y}$. 
%[text] We can evaluate the probabilities using the `bino_` family of functions. 
% Set parameters for the binomial distribution
n =20; %[control:slider:3007]{"position":[4,6]}
p = 0.35; %[control:slider:5413]{"position":[5,9]}

y = 0:n;
binomial_density = binopdf(y, n, p);
binomial_distribution = binocdf(y, n, p);

% Plot the Binomial density function
stem(y, binomial_density); %[output:38e9dbcb]
title('Density of Binomial(n,p)'); %[output:38e9dbcb]
xlabel('y'); %[output:38e9dbcb]
ylabel('Probability mass'); %[output:38e9dbcb]
grid on; %[output:38e9dbcb]

% Plot the Binomial distribution function
stairs(y, binomial_distribution); %[output:629f8083]
title('Distribution function of Binomial(n,p)'); %[output:629f8083]
xlabel('y'); %[output:629f8083]
ylabel('Cumulative density'); %[output:629f8083]
grid on; %[output:629f8083]
%[text] To answer the questions, keep note of the fact that, for any nonempty $A\\subseteq\\{0,\\dots,n\\}$ and integer $k$, $\\mathbb{P}\\{Y\\in A\\} = \\sum\_{y\\in A}f(y)$ and
%[text]{"align":"center"} $\\mathbb{P}\\{Y \< k\\} = \\mathbb{P}\\{Y\\leq k - 1\\} = F(k - 1)$,
%[text] where $F$ is the distribution function. For our questions, set $n = 20$ and $p = 0.35$.
binopdf(5, n, p) %[output:41dc4b68]
binocdf(14, n, p) - binocdf(4, n, p) % also sum(binopdf(5:14, n, p)) %[output:9b5cd8ee]
binocdf(15, n, p) - binocdf(5, n, p) % also sum(binopdf(6:15, n, p)) %[output:514adb8b]
sum(binopdf([1,5,9,17], n, p)) %[output:3858f8b8]
1 - sum(binopdf([5, 13, 16], n, p)) %[output:4d5d17a2]
%[text] To answer part (b), consider the success of each test question as a Bernoulli distribution, where the probability of getting a particular question correct is $1/5$—or more generally $1/m$, where $m$ is the number of options available per question. Let $Y$ be the number of questions the student guesses correctly. Then $Y\\sim\\text{Bin}(n,p)$, where $n$ is the number of questions and $p$ is the probability of correctly guessing any particular question correct. The probability that *all the questions are guessed correctly* is $\\mathbb{P}\\{Y = n\\} = f(n) = p^{n}$. The probability that the student passes any given test with $n$ questions— scores at least $n / 2$—is given by  
%[text]{"align":"center"} $\\mathbb{P}\\left\\{Y \\geq \\frac{n}{2}\\right\\} = 1 - \\mathbb{P}\\left\\{Y \< \\frac{n}{2}\\right\\} =1 - \\mathbb{P}\\left\\{Y\\leq\\left\\lfloor\\frac{n - 1}{2}\\right\\rfloor\\right\\} = 1 - F\\left(\\left\\lfloor\\frac{n - 1}{2}\\right\\rfloor\\right).$
numberQuestions = 10;
choicesPerQuestion = 5;
probabilityQuestionCorrect = 1 / choicesPerQuestion;

% probability of guessing everything correctly
binopdf(numberQuestions, numberQuestions, probabilityQuestionCorrect)  %[output:5e79acc1]
probabilityQuestionCorrect^numberQuestions %[output:7ece34a8]

% probability of passing a test
failingMark = floor((numberQuestions - 1) / 2); % use floor to identify the failing mark for both even and odd cases
1 - binocdf(failingMark, numberQuestions, probabilityQuestionCorrect) %[output:4529548d]
% we can use the argument 'upper' to calculate the strict tail probability Pr{Y > y}
passProbability = binocdf(failingMark, numberQuestions, probabilityQuestionCorrect, 'upper') %[output:6132395c]

%[text] We can treat the event of passing a single test as a Bernoulli random variable with parameter `passProbability`. Suppose that there are $K$ identically structured tests in the term and let $Z$ be the number of tests passed. Then $Z\\sim\\text{Bin}(K,\\texttt{passProbability})$. The probability of passing at least one exam is
%[text]{"align":"center"} $\\mathbb{P}(Y \\geq 1) = 1 - \\mathbb{P}(Y \< 1) = 1 - \\mathbb{P}(Y \\leq 0) = 1 - f\_{Y}(0) = 1 - (1 - \\texttt{passProbability})^{K}$.
numberExams = 3;
1 - binocdf(0, numberExams, passProbability) %[output:40ced378]
%%
%[text] ## Question 2
%[text] Suppose that some event occurs indpendently at a constant mean rate. Then the number of events which occur in some bounded time or space is given by the Poisson distribution with parameter $\\lambda \> 0$, where $\\lambda$ is the mean rate of occurrence. The Poisson distribution has support on the nonnegative integers $\\mathbb{N}\_{0} = \\{0,1,2,\\dots,\\}$and has mass function $f(k) = \\lambda^{k}\\mathrm{e}^{-\\lambda} / k!$. 
lambda =7; %[control:slider:2a65]{"position":[9,10]}
x = 0:poissinv(0.999,lambda);
poissonDensity = poisspdf(x, lambda);
poissonDistribution = poisscdf(x, lambda);

% Plot the Poisson density function
stem(x, poissonDensity) %[output:308e9268]
title('Density of Poisson($\lambda$)', 'Interpreter','latex') %[output:308e9268]
xlabel('x') %[output:308e9268]
ylabel('Probability mass') %[output:308e9268]
grid on; %[output:308e9268]

% Plot the Poisson distribution function
stairs(x, poissonDistribution) %[output:351bd32e]
title('Distribution function of Poisson($\lambda$)', 'Interpreter','latex') %[output:351bd32e]
xlabel('x') %[output:351bd32e]
ylabel('Cumulative density') %[output:351bd32e]
grid on; %[output:351bd32e]

%[text] The Poisson distribution has discrete support, so computation will be similar to Question 1. 
poisscdf(3, lambda) %[output:5b5e762e]
poisscdf(2, lambda) %[output:7d1e1596]
sum(poisspdf([19, 20], lambda)) %[output:0c889fa8]
1 - poisscdf(0, lambda) %[output:8c80e53a]
%[text] Suppose that astronomers find on average *one star per 16* $\\textit{ly}^{3}$—this is the mean rate of occurrence. Let $X$ denote the number of stars we find in a random 16 cubic light year area. We may consider $X\\sim\\text{Pois}(\\lambda = 1)$ since the region we are observing is bounded. The probability of finding at least two stars in a 16$\\textit{ly}^{3}$ region is
%[text]{"align":"center"} $\\mathbb{P}\\{X\\geq 2\\} = 1 - \\mathbb{P}\\{X \< 2\\} = 1 - \\mathbb{P}\\{X\\leq 1\\} = 1 - F(1\\vert \\lambda = 1).$
1 - poisscdf(1, 1) %[output:9f01f65f]
%[text] We wish to determine the volume of space which we should observe so that the probability of observing at least one star is 95%. Let $n$ denote the number of 16$\\textit{ly}^{3}$ blocks that we observe. We wish to solve the statement
%[text]{"align":"center"} $\\mathbb{P}(nX \\geq 1) \> 0.95$
%[text] for $n$. Note that $nX =: X\_{n}\\sim Poiss(n\\lambda)$ since we treat the presence of stars in any region to be independent. Thus,
%[text]{"align":"center"} $\\mathbb{P}(X\_{n}\\geq 1) = 1 - \\mathbb{P}(X\_{n} = 0) = 1 - \\mathrm{e}^{n\\lambda}$.
%[text] Rearranging and solving for $n$ yields the inequality $n \> -\\log(0.05) / \\lambda$. Hence, we should view at least $-16\\times\\log(0.05) \\approx 47.93$ cubic light years of space so that we can see at least one star with 95% probability. 
-log(0.05) % how many 16 ly^3 blocks should we observe %[output:5585857d]
-16 * log(0.05) % convert this to actual volume of space %[output:4a266657]
%[text] *How would this answer change if we wanted to know the number of intersections to observe to record at least one car crash with probability 0.95?*
%%
%[text] ## Question 3
%[text] Let $X\\sim U(a,b)$, where $a$ and $b$ are the bounds of $X$, with $a\\leq b$. The Uniform distribution is continuous and, for $a \< x \< b$, has density $f(x) = (b - a)^{-1}$ and distribution $F(x) = (x - a) / (b - a)$.  Continuity of the density implies that $X$ taking any discrete set of values has probability 0. For example, let $A,B\\subset (a,b)$, where $A$ and $B$ are respectively finite and countable. Then $\\mathbb{P}\\{X\\in A\\} = \\mathbb{P}\\{X\\in B\\} = 0$. In particular, for $a \< x \< b$, 
%[text]{"align":"center"} $F(x) = \\mathbb{P}\\{X \\leq x\\} = \\mathbb{P}\\{X \< x\\} \\cup\\{X = x\\} = \\mathbb{P}\\{X \< x\\} + \\mathbb{P}\\{X = x\\} = \\mathbb{P}\\{X \< x\\}.$
%[text] Hence, for$X\\sim U\[-1,1\]$, we have $\\mathbb{P}\\{X \< 0\\} = \\mathbb{P}\\{X \\leq 0\\} = F(0)$ and 
%[text]{"align":"center"} $\\mathbb{P}\\{-0.9\\leq X\\leq 0.8\\} = \\mathbb{P}\\{X \\leq 0.8\\} - \\mathbb{P}\\{X\<-0.9\\} = \\mathbb{P}\\{X \\leq 0.8\\} - \\mathbb{P}\\{X\\leq-0.9\\} = F(0.8) - F(-0.9)$.
range =[-1 1] %[control:rangeslider:939c]{"position":[8,14]} %[output:2280df92]
a = range(1);
b = range(2);

x = linspace(a - 0.2, b + 0.2, 1000);
uniformDensity = unifpdf(x, a, b);
uniformDistribution = unifcdf(x, a, b);

plot(x, uniformDensity); %[output:4a6bb4ce]
ylim([0, max(uniformDensity) * 1.2]); % extend the y-limits so that the density doesn't coincide with the ceiling %[output:4a6bb4ce]
xlabel('x');  %[output:4a6bb4ce]
ylabel('Density'); %[output:4a6bb4ce]
title('Uniform(a,b) density'); %[output:4a6bb4ce]
grid on; %[output:4a6bb4ce]

plot(x, uniformDistribution); %[output:6b921754]
xlabel('x');  %[output:6b921754]
ylabel('P(X < x)', 'Interpreter','latex'); %[output:6b921754]
title('Uniform(a,b) distribution function'); %[output:6b921754]
ylim([-0.05 1.05]); %[output:6b921754]
grid on; %[output:6b921754]
%[text] 
% set a = -1 and b = 1
% matlab default arguments are a = 0 and b = 1
unifcdf(0, a, b) %[output:2900c8a3]
unifcdf(0.8, a, b) - unifcdf(-0.9, a, b) %[output:90b385e9]
%[text] We now want to determine where the 90% of the $U\[-1,1\]$ distribution is located—determine $x\_{\*}$ such that $\\mathbb{P}\\{-x\_{\*} \\leq X \\leq x\_{\*}\\} = 0.9$. By symmetry $\\mathbb{P}\\{-x\_{\*} \\leq X \\leq x\_{\*}\\} = 2\\mathbb{P}\\{X \\leq x\_{\*}\\} - 1$, which implies that $x\_{\*}$ satisfies $\\mathbb{P}\\{X\\leq x\_{\*}\\} = 0.95$. Finding $x\_{\*}$ is the reverse opposite (*or inverse*) computation for the distribution function—also known as finding the quantiles. Symbolically, if $F^{-1}$ is the quantile function, then $x\_{\*} = F^{-1}(0.95)$. We can use `unifinv()` to find the necessary quantiles here.
unifinv(0.95, a, b) %[output:48f681a4]
%[text] To answer part (b), set $a = 0.2050$ and $b = 0.2150$. Note that 0.2125 is the midpoint of $(a,b)$, so $\\mathbb{P}\\{X \> 0.2125\\} = \\mathbb{P}\\{X \\leq 0.2125\\} = 0.5$. 
unifinv(1 - 0.1, 0.2050, 0.2150) %[output:8e96aec0]
%%
%[text] ## Question 6
n = 100; %[control:slider:4c59]{"position":[5,8]}
% generate n-by-1 array
% MATLAB will generate an n-by-n array by default
normal = normrnd(3, 4, n, 1);
uniform = unifrnd(0, 1, n, 1);
exponential = exprnd(4, n, 1);
binomial = binornd(20, 0.9, n, 1);
poisson = poissrnd(9, n, 1);

% Plug data into a single cell array
dataVectors = {normal, uniform, exponential, binomial, poisson};
names = {'Normal', 'Uniform', 'Exponential', 'Binomial', 'Poisson'};
colors = lines(length(names));

figure %[output:4761b2e6]
for i = 1:5 %[output:group:059c98a0]
    subplot(2, 3, i) %[output:4761b2e6]
    h = qqplot(dataVectors{i});
    h(1).MarkerEdgeColor = colors(i,:);
    h(1).MarkerFaceColor = colors(i,:);
    h(2).Color = colors(i,:);
    h(3).Color = colors(i,:);
    title(names{i})
end %[output:group:059c98a0]
%[text] Let's take a look at a quantile plot for real data. Recall the `inflows` data set, where we observed that the values were significantly right-skewed. 
[~, inflow] = readvars("data\inflows.txt");

figure %[output:500e243d]
qqplot(inflow) %[output:500e243d]
title("Quantile plot for inflows") %[output:500e243d]

qqplot(log(inflow)) %[output:63b6fd41]
title("Quantile plot for log(inflows)") %[output:63b6fd41]

